			<div class="description">
				The ATA works is exactly like our brain does with our two ears to help us tell what direction a sound is coming from. If a sound comes from in front of us or behind us, it arrives at both ears at the same time. If the sound comes from our left, it arrives in our left ear just a little before it gets to the right ear. If we want to concentrate on sounds coming from certain directions, our 'computer' (out brain) is so sophisticated that we can concentrate on things from several directions and filter out the rest - and we do that with only <em>two ears!</em>. The human brain is much more sophisticated than any computers we can build, so the ATA uses 42 'ears' to focus on specific directions.
      </div>
      <div class="description">
        The advantage of an array over a single large dish is that the signals from these dishes can be combined in special ways by computer to electronically point it in several directions <em>at the same time</em>, with each circular spot about as small as what you get in only one direction with a single big dish. With <%= link_to "setilive.org", "setilive.org" %> we look at 'waterfall' images, which show the radio signals received in these directions by the ATA over a certain frequency range and how it changes over the 90 seconds or so before the ATA switches to a new direction or frequency range (more about waterfall images later). The SETI scientists have automated computer algorithms to analyze these images and look for signals that might be worth a second look.
        </div>
        <div class="description">Computer algorithms however don't work very well when there are also strong signals coming from earthbound and orbiting signal sources. Unfortunately humans use radio signals a lot to communicate with each other like from satellites and WiFi and to make matters worse, non-radio electronics (like digital cameras and computers) produce unintentional radio signals as a byproduct of their normal operation. This means that while trying to listen for faint radio signals from space the telescope will also pick up a lot of Radio Frequency Interference (RFI) here on Earth. One of the hardest parts of hunting for signals from space is separating what might be an ET signal from the earth-based RFI sources.We think that the sophisticated human eyes and the brain attached to them should be better than a computer at finding interesting, possible ET signals in the waterfall images, especially when there's RFI.
			</div>
		</div>

 		<div data-animation-scene="Radiosphere" class="radiosphere scene">
