			<div class="description">The radiosphere is the spherical region of space around the Earth within which an ET civilization would be close enough to detect our radio signals. About 70 years ago, we started producing signals that could get beyond our ionosphere and radiate into space.  Radio waves are actually a form of light and so travel at the same speed as all forms of light, or 299,792,458 meters per second. This finite speed means that it takes radio waves some time to travel from one point to another. Normally, on Earth the distance between emitter and detector is small enough that it appears to happen instantaneously.</div>

      <div class="description">However, the nearest star that is known to have a planet is Epsilon Eridani, 10 light-years away. This is a huge distance, about 100 million million kilometres. It takes light 10 years to travel this distance from Earth but this planet is well within our radiosphere. Our signals haven't had time to reach planets more than 70 light-years away, so there's no chance they could detect them (yet). Another problem is that radio waves spread out over space as they travel further and further, so an ET civilization's antenna intercepts less and less power. At very large distances, ETs might have to construct huge antennas to collect more power to address this problem and an advanced civilization should be capable of this.</div>

      <div class="description">The radiosphere works in reverse as well, but we don't know when an ET civilization started producing signals that could escape their ionosphere, so we don't know how large a distant star's radio sphere would be. SETILive is about looking for signals that ET civilizations are producing. There's a chance that a civilization is routinely sending signals towards us in a very narrow, high power beam (maybe in response to detecting signals from our direction) and we have a fair chance of detecting that.</div>
